  "description": "TF-Java reference for the small-mesh anisotropic-UPML tensor-\u03b5 dielectric-sphere Mie eigenmode pipeline (Epic #88 / Phase J.5 / Issue #174). TF-Java JVM driver (reference/tf_java/sphere_mie) does the per-element N\u00e9d\u00e9lec curl-curl + diagonal-tensor complex-\u03b5 mass assembly via static-graph Ops + Session: the per-tet (\u03b5_x, \u03b5_y, \u03b5_z) tensor enters as two parallel [nTets, 3] f64 placeholders (TF-Java 1.0.0 has no native c128 typed value) and the per-axis cofactor gram gg^(\u03b1)_pq = g_p[\u03b1] g_q[\u03b1] is contracted against it inside the graph, emitting Re(M) and Im(M) as parallel f64 tensors. The Python driver (reference/driver/eigensolve_from_sidecar.py --problem sphere-mie --backend tfjava) fuses the (Re, Im) pair into a SciPy complex128 pencil and runs dense LAPACK ZGGEV (matching reference/numpy/sphere_mie.py). NO sign canonicalization: physical Im(\u03bb) < 0 on this small mesh's tensor pencil \u2014 a property of the pencil, not a solver choice (J.2 fixture description). \u03c3\u2080 = 5.0, k\u2080_ref = 2.0. NumPy J.2 canonical (PR #179) `physical_eigenvalues_complex`: physical[0] |\u0394| = 0.000e+00; per-position max |\u0394| = 0.000e+00 over 5 entries (dense LAPACK ZGGEV both sides \u2014 strict per-position diff). TF-Java JVM scatterNd accumulation order is bit-equivalent to NumPy COO->CSR within scatter-order ULP; the eigensolve matches dense LAPACK ZGGEV exactly when called via the sidecar driver (--problem sphere-mie --backend tfjava).",
  "units": "\u03bb = k\u00b2 (inverse-length squared) under exp(+j\u03c9t); dimensionless mesh coordinates",
